IMF needs more Lagarde
Davos — Lagarde said she is open to serving another five years as IMF Managing Director.
She should stay.
IMF has never had better leadership than her, and the IMF Board should give her the opportunity to complete the work she started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, taking over an institution in crisis.
The 2008 global financial crash and its economic aftermath tarnished the reputation of Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the free-market "Washington consensus."
Lagarde's leadership helped the IMF restore its credibility.
Many have focused on her personal qualities — as they should.
She is honest, strong, warm, and compelling.
Officials from around the world who have met her (often in delicate situations) have all praised her for being willing to speak the difficult realities, while also being a sensitive listener.
These are important qualities for a leader of an institution that must negotiate terms of agreements rather than dominate everything.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed restructuring, or else firewalls must be built to prevent financial contagion. It was harsh advice, but the Europeans followed it.
Similarly, she loudly urged support from the IMF to several countries — such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — which is crucial for global stability.
There are countless examples.
The IMF is not good at innovation and is usually not passionate.
Lagarde began to change this.
In the process, she gave the institution, which often prescribed harsh remedies, a human face.
For example, managing the refugee crisis in the Middle East was not originally within the IMF's mandate.
But under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its plan to allow the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to help those displaced by the Syrian and Iraqi conflicts (over one million people living in refugee camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak erupted in West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF to use its available funds to grant debt relief to affected countries, enabling them to improve the treatment of doctors and nurses — this was the first time the IMF used its own capital in this manner.
Additionally, Lagarde recognized that the world today faces three of the most important challenges, and she took action on them.
First, she strongly urged more women to join the workforce, and she herself is a living example of the value of women in leadership positions.
In a variety of countries, from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop wasting such a huge human resource — and thus realize economic potential.
Second, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a matter of basic fairness.
IMF's research emphasizes a direct link between reducing inequality and boosting economic growth.
IMF is not the first institution to demonstrate this, but its position makes the issue more prominent and urgent.
Lagarde has personally been committed to promoting this point, which was key to increasing its urgency.
Third, Lagarde played an important role in helping the world recognize the full impact of technological change — some of which will cause alarming disruptive effects.
For example, automation will continue to increase manufacturing efficiency and reduce its costs, but it also means that the number of jobs generated by economic growth will be less than before.
The political, economic, and social consequences of this emerging reality are worth recognizing and serious study.
Lagarde made the IMF the core of this effort.
Critics would say it is time for IMF to be led by representatives from developing countries.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th consecutive European to hold this position, and Europe's possession of such privilege is difficult to justify in today's world.
Some would also argue that the austerity measures supported by the IMF in Greece did not achieve significant results, proving that she has become disconnected from the general public.
Some would also point out that she faces allegations of involvement in a financial scandal in France, which would distract her from her IMF work.
Critics argue that after her predecessor Dominique Strauss-Kahn was embroiled in a scandal, the IMF must never again be distracted by such incidents.
We will now examine these objections one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside of Europe and the United States.
But the goal of ending this Western privilege is to base the leader selection process on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best choice to be IMF Managing Director, and emerging powers such as the BRICS countries (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) did not jointly propose an alternative candidate.
Having an European person as IMF Managing Director might also have been one of the favorable factors in the IMF's decision last year to include the RMB in the currency basket that determines the value of the SDR.
In addition, Lagarde demonstrated impressive political flexibility, ultimately persuading both the Republican and Democratic Congresses in the United States to approve IMF governance reforms. These reforms not only strengthened the IMF's arsenal against financial crises, but also more accurately reflected the changing dynamics of the global economy.
For example, the BRICS countries are now among the top ten shareholders of the IMF.
On the issue of Greece, Lagarde made some notably candid — and some would say inappropriate — comments last year.
But she is certainly not the culprit who brought economic pain to the Greeks. Her tenure at the IMF has clearly shown that no IMF Managing Director in history has done as much as she has to lead the IMF in alleviating the suffering of people in crises.
Finally, the French accusations against Lagarde were opposed by the French prosecutor general, and Lagarde was at most only slightly involved.
The world urgently needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has proven that she is exactly such a leader, committed to making the IMF adapt to the twenty-first century.
She should be given the opportunity to see her work through to the end.
